## Case Study: Sanrita.ca

**URL:** https://sanrita.ca

**Confidence note:** this section now separates direct observations from reconstruction guidance. It is meant to help recreate the feel of the site without pretending we have the source animation code.

### Key Techniques

#### 1. Loading as a Same-World Staged Reveal

San Rita should not be treated as a normal loading-bar case study. The stronger read is a **same-world staged reveal**: the loading copy, transition layer, and final hero all belong to one cartographic universe, so the user feels like the site is expanding into focus rather than swapping from loader to homepage.

##### Observed in the live page

- A fixed `.c-preload-overlay` sits above the page with a high z-index and a pale terrain-colored background.
- A fixed `.c-transition-wrapper` with a full-screen `canvas` sits behind the main content.
- The hero already uses the same world language as the loading state: terrain imagery, route/path motifs, grid framing, waypoints, and the CTA `Scroll to enter our world`.
- The loader text is narrative and world-building (`Terraforming activated`, `Known trails emerging`, `Viewpoints activated`) rather than generic system status text.
- The page structure suggests continuity, not replacement: the load phase and the hero phase are visually related layers of the same scene.

##### What matters about the animation

- The important effect is **expansion and settling**, not percentage feedback.
- The image language feels like a drawing or mapped world resolving outward until it becomes the landing scene.
- Depth comes from several visual planes coexisting: background terrain, route overlays, grid/guide systems, UI rails, and large type.
- The motion likely avoids linear timing. The feel is more cinematic and eased, with a soft settle into the hero instead of a hard cut.

##### Recreate the effect like this

1. Start with the final world already designed.
2. Put the intro in an earlier state of that same world.
3. Reveal the world by expanding scale, mask area, visible route length, and layer opacity together.
4. Let foreground UI and labels settle last so the page feels like it has landed.
5. Keep continuity in palette, motifs, and geometry so the loader feels like the hero waking up.

##### Practical build pattern

```html
<div class="transition-stage">
  <canvas class="transition-atmosphere"></canvas>

  <div class="preload-overlay">
    <div class="preload-copy">
      <p>Terraforming activated</p>
      <p>Known trails emerging</p>
      <p>Viewpoints activated</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <main class="hero-world">
    <div class="world-terrain"></div>
    <svg class="world-routes"></svg>
    <div class="world-grid"></div>
    <aside class="world-rail"></aside>
    <h1 class="world-cta">Scroll to enter our world</h1>
  </main>
</div>
```

##### Recommended motion recipe

```javascript
// Recreation guidance, not verified San Rita source code
const tl = gsap.timeline();

tl.fromTo('.hero-world',
  { scale: 1.06, opacity: 0.7 },
  { scale: 1, opacity: 1, duration: 1.6, ease: 'power2.out' }
)
  .fromTo('.world-routes',
    { drawSVG: '0% 0%', opacity: 0.3 },
    { drawSVG: '0% 100%', opacity: 1, duration: 1.4, ease: 'power2.inOut' },
    0.1
  )
  .fromTo('.world-grid, .world-rail',
    { y: 24, opacity: 0 },
    { y: 0, opacity: 1, duration: 0.9, stagger: 0.08, ease: 'power3.out' },
    0.45
  )
  .to('.preload-overlay',
    { opacity: 0, duration: 0.35, ease: 'power2.out' },
    0.9
  );
```

##### Easing guidance

- Use **decelerating curves** for reveal and landing: `power2.out`, `power3.out`, or a custom cinematic bezier.
- Use **gentle in-out timing** for route drawing and mask growth so the world feels like it is unfolding, not being switched on.
- If the transition relies heavily on scale, `expoScale`-style motion is a good recreation tool because it keeps zooming from feeling visually lumpy.
- Avoid linear counters or mechanically stepped progress unless the brand intentionally wants a system-UI mood.

##### What to stop claiming as fact

- Do not describe San Rita as a conventional progress-bar loader.
- Do not claim exact timeline durations, staggers, or named eases unless verified from source.
- Do not present inferred GSAP internals, clip-path usage, or route-drawing implementation as confirmed truth.
- Treat the terraforming copy as one layer of the experience, not the whole animation system.

